   in cooperation with ECN Petten.                                2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       2834 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               2834 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       2834 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     2834 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  2834 1451
VI   (Mod3) evaluation by Larson, C. Perey, Hetrich, and          2834 1451
Fu.                                                               2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 2 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        2834 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             2834 1451
significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    2834 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   2834 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  2834 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    2834 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    2834 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        2834 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      2834 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   2834 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     2834 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                2834 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   2834 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           2834 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         2834 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      2834 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         2834 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     2834 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      2834 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    2834 1451
Ni58 and p + Ni58 reactions (Ch97). We use the GNASH code system  2834 1451
(Yo92), which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               2834 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    2834 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       2834 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     2834 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    2834 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    2834 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  2834 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       2834 1451
(Ka88).                                                           2834 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  2834 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations (Ch96). The recoil    2834 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  2834 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     2834 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   2834 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  2834 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             2834 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  2834 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach (Ka77,      2834 1451
Ka85), validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  2834 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     2834 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     2834 1451
using the formulation of Gilbert and Cameron (Gi65) and pairing   2834 1451
and shell parameters from the Cook (Co67) analysis. Neutron and   2834 1451
charged- particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    2834 1451
the optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray            2834 1451
transmission coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl   2834 1451
model (Ko90).                                                     2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
SOME Ni-SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THE EVAL.                 2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
  The neutron total cross section was evaluated based on the      2834 1451
least-squares method with GMA code system (Po81) taking account of2834 1451
the experimental data(Ci68, Pe73, Sc73, La83, Sm92, Di97).  The   2834 1451
data for natural Ni and Ni-58 were used because there was no data 2834 1451
for Ni-61.  These data were transformed to the Ni-61 cross section2834 1451
according to A*(2/3) law.  In the GMA analysis, the systematic    2834 1451
error was assumed to be 1 % for all the data set.  Result of the  2834 1451
GMA evaluation was used as the evaluated total cross section data 2834 1451
above 20 MeV.                                                     2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
The evaluated total cross section data (1 to 250 MeV) and s-wave  2834 1451
strength function (Mu81) were used to obtain the neutron optical  2834 1451
potential parameters.  The parameter estimation was carried out   2834 1451
based on Marquart-Bayesian approach (Sm91), where ECIS95 code was 2834 1451
used for the optical model calculation.  We have employed the     2834 1451
energy dependence of the optical potential similar to Delaroche's 2834 1451
work(De89).  The initial potential parameters were adopted from   2834 1451
Koning and Delaroche (Ko97).  Total of 7 parameters concerning the2834 1451
central potential depth were estimated with associated covariance 2834 1451
matrix, while the geometrical parameters were fixed to the result 2834 1451
of a similar search for n + Ni-58.  Presently obtained potential  2834 1451
was used for the calculation of neutron transmission coefficients 2834 1451
and DWBA cross sections in the energy region above 20 MeV.  Below 2834 1451
20 MeV, the Harper neutron potential (Ha82) was used for the      2834 1451
calculation of transmission coefficients.                         2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
The proton optical potential was also searched for to obtain a    2834 1451
good description of proton-total reaction cross section as        2834 1451
predicted by Wellisch-Axen systematic (We96) above 50 MeV.  The   2834 1451
parameter estimation was carried out by the Marquart-Bayesian     2834 1451
approach similar to the neutron OMP, but trying to seek the best  2834 1451
parameter to reproduce the reaction cross sections compiled by    2834 1451
Carlson (Ca96) and Wellisch values. The experimental data in      2834 1451
Carlson (Ca96) was scaled for Ni-61 according to A**(2/3) law.  In2834 1451
this search, the geometrical parameters were fixed to be same as  2834 1451
the neutron potential.  The present potential gives a good        2834 1451
description of the proton total reaction cross section from 10 MeV2834 1451
to 250 MeV.  However, after some trial and error to reproduce both2834 1451
the elastic scattering and reaction cross section data for Ni-58, 2834 1451
we have employed the following combination of proton potentials:  2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
 0 to   5 MeV  :  Harper potential (Ha82)                         2834 1451
 6 to  47 MeV  :  Koning and Delaroche (Ko97)                     2834 1451
48 to 260 MeV  :  Present OMP                                     2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
For deuterons, the Lohr-Haeberli (Lo74) global potential was used;2834 1451
for alpha particles the McFadden-Satchler (Mc66) potential was    2834 1451
used; and for tritons the Becchetti-Greenlees (Be71) potential was2834 1451
used.  The He-3 channel was ignored.                              2834 1451
                                                                  2834 1451
The direct collective inelastic scattering to the following levels2834 1451
